reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:74:      "difference": "Pargament is a psychology of religion model, not a source-sensitive comparative protocol that codes claimant grammar and translation strain before credit.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:77:      "source": "Kenneth Pargament et al., Religion and the Problem-Solving Process: Three Styles of Coping, summary at https://icmglt.org/icmlibrary/religion-and-the-problem-solving-process-three-styles-of-coping/"
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:112:      "overlap": "Very close primary-tradition prior for credit grammar. Shinran already makes claimability, causation, teacher ownership, practice merit, and transformation depend on Other Power.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:113:      "source": "Shinran and Tannisho, Other Power and self-power distinctions, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:133:    "Use low-strain tests first: Tannisho self-power and Other Power, Srivaishnava surrender debates, Sufi maqam and hal, and Bhagavad Gita action, fruit, and doership passages.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:135:    "Compare predictive power against Pargament agency styles, religious attribution theory, Lindbeck grammar, Asad discursive tradition, Freiberger comparative method, VCE variables, upaya pedagogy, grace and effort theology, institution, teacher style, social ecology, and clinical risk.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:140:  "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.73 to about 0.47. The candidate is useful, but most components have close priors: Pargament and attribution theory for agency and causal credit, Lindbeck and Asad for grammar and authorized practice, Freiberger, Smith, Sandmel, Katz, and comparative-theology methods for strain and category caution, VCE for multidimensional controls, and prior Lumenary ledgers for credit, claimability, custody, residue, and translation strain. The surviving contribution is not a doctrine candidate or strong discovery. It is a bounded split-source testing protocol for whether credit distribution adds predictive power after claimant grammar and translation strain are coded.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:146:      "Is this more than Pargament, attribution theory, grace and effort theology, upaya, or doctrine-as-grammar in new language?",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:152:      "Psychologists of religion familiar with Pargament and attribution theory",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:166:      "Tannisho chapters 1, 3, 6, 8, and 16, BDK English Tripitaka translation, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:169:    "secondary_literature_gap": "The audit used accessible translations and open secondary sources but did not read Sanskrit, Japanese, Tamil, Arabic, Pali, or Tibetan originals. It did not fully reread Lindbeck, Katz, Clooney, J. Z. Smith, Sandmel, Rambo, or Pargament's full article corpus. It also lacks practitioner interviews and statistical comparison against existing models.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:170:    "structural_observation": "The Gita is a strong test case for why credit needs claimant grammar first. It preserves obligation to act, denies simple ego-doership, separates action from fruits, and lists multiple causes of action, including bodily basis, instruments, effort, and divine factor. A simple self versus God credit scale misses that action, fruit, ego, duty, and causation are differently distributed. Tannisho creates a sharper strain case. It relocates efficacy to Amida's Vow, rejects self-powered merit, denies Shinran ownership over disciples, and describes nembutsu as neither ordinary practice nor good act because it arises through Other Power. Coding both texts with the same deferring or collaborative category would flatten native rules about what kind of action is even claimable. The close read supports the candidate's sequence, but it also shows that the primary traditions already force much of the insight."
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:179:  "unlike_statement": "Unlike Pargament's agency styles, attribution theory, Lindbeck's grammar, Asad's discursive tradition, Freiberger's comparative method, and prior Lumenary credit and strain ledgers, this idea's distinct claim is a narrow testing order: code native claimant grammar and translation strain first, then ask whether stage-level credit distribution adds independent prediction of safeguards, warnings, repairs, or transition vulnerabilities. Without that added predictive gain, the idea is mostly a renamed consolidation of existing comparison and agency-allocation methods."
