reviews/originality/2026-05-26-threshold-grammar-under-translation-strain-63091c8c41cd9e28.json:182:    "structural_observation": "Tannisho gives a vow-held entry grammar: the decisive threshold is firm entrusting in Amida's vow, with warnings against self-effort, esoteric seeking, and arbitrary interpretation. Orange gives a grace-first Christian entry grammar: even prayer, will, desire, faith, and assent are preceded by grace, so anti-Pelagian safeguards are structurally expected. SN 55.5 gives a different threshold grammar: association with admirable people, hearing true Dhamma, appropriate attention, and practice in accordance with Dhamma. It predicts safeguards around community, teaching, attention, and right practice, not grace or vow. Dogen's Bendowa strains the model because practice and realization are not two sequential states; the warning is against waiting for enlightenment outside practice. These texts support the idea that entry accounts predict warning profiles, but they also show high translation strain: grace, vow, stream-entry, and practice-realization are not interchangeable values of one neutral variable."
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-prescriptive-custody-of-beginnings-7a1a4b07a241a1b9.json:31:      "test_surface": "Split-source blind coding across Orange, Tannisho or Ofumi, Benedictine novitiate texts, OCIA, SN 55.5 and related Theravada manuals, one Dzogchen or Mahamudra entry source, and one Sufi or Islamic initiation source.",
