reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:77:        "Add source coding for whether return language is native, permitted, or imported in Dogen, Shinran, MN 22, Heart Sutra, Rinzai, and comparable Christian or Sufi materials.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:82:      "original_claim": "A practice-routing model must decide three things before recommending a return test: whether the practice permits result language, whether the practitioner is presently bypassing or self-scoring, and who should hold the diagnostic gate. Self-administered return attention may help the bypasser who uses insight to avoid conduct. For the compulsive scorer, the gate should be externally held by a teacher, peer, clinician, fixed rule, or replaced by resultless practice. For oscillators, the assignment must be state-level and revisable, not a stable identity label.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:97:        "Challenger revision pressure: non-instrumental traditions such as Dogen practice-realization and Shinran no-calculation require a scope gate before result custody language is applied.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:142:        "note": "Many perfectionists may move between bypassing and compulsive scoring, so the gate should ask what is happening now rather than assign a stable identity.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:179:    "unresolved_crux": "Whether the gate can reliably distinguish bypassing from compulsive self-scoring in the moment, and whether people whose wound is self-evaluation can safely self-administer that gate without turning the repair into another score."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:181:  "title": "Whether the gate can reliably distinguish bypassing from compulsive self-scoring...",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:194:        "The second pressure, kept versus released versus embodied, is a genuine contribution and rightly refuses to make raft-release universal.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:196:        "For the bypassing, insight-floating member of the cohort, redirecting attention from the peak to the return is sound and helpful."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:198:      "counter_model": "Put a scope gate before the return test. First ask whether the practice claims to make anything at all. For the instrumental band, do this and get that, the two-pressure return test is exactly right. But a large class of practice refuses the frame at the root: Dogen's practice-realization says the sitting is not a means to a later enlightenment, so there is no result to return from, and Shinran's jinen honi says there is no calculation by the practicer, so there is no outcome a self could own. For these the return question is not answered, it is dissolved. More pointedly for this cohort: the lever that frees a compulsive self-measurer is a practice that offers nothing to evaluate, not a wiser evaluation. So the correct first move for the perfectionist may be a resultless practice, not a refined return audit, and the return test, applied to its own target, may reinstall the scoring engine one level up by making the quality of my return the new thing to grade.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:204:      "new_source": "Iris B. Mor and Jennifer Winquist, Self-Focused Attention and Negative Affect: A Meta-Analysis, Psychological Bulletin 2002, complicates the claim directly: self-focused attention reliably amplifies negative affect, and the effect is strongest for people prone to rumination and self-evaluation, which is precisely the perfectionistic, achievement-contingent cohort this practice recruits. A repeated, structured self-check that asks such a person to rate pride, shame, and comparison after every session is the intervention most likely to deepen the very self-monitoring it means to relieve. As a primary control on the other side, Shinran's Tannisho and jinen honi, no calculation by the practicer, names a tradition whose entire remedy for self-effort exhaustion is the cessation of self-administered tests, not a better one, which is what an exhausted achiever may actually need.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:210:        "Shinran, Tannisho, and jinen honi (no working, no calculation by the practicer), Matheson Trust translation",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:211:        "Dogen, Bendowa, shusho-itto (practice and realization are one)",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:215:      "steelman": "The strongest form of this idea is not a sorting grid; it is a relocation of where a practice proves itself. Instead of asking whether a session produced a vivid experience, it asks what the person carries back into speech, work, and care for others, and treats that re-entry as the only honest measure of completion. The two pressures are well chosen: whether the method lets a result stand or undermines the claim to have one, and whether the method is then kept, set down, or lived as conduct. That second pressure is genuinely useful, because it predicts different aftercare for a koan curriculum than for a raft, and it refuses to make raft-release the universal pattern. And the human aim is real and well evidenced: achievement-contingent self-worth, perfectionism, and burnout are documented and rising, and the teaching line, let a practice change your conduct before it becomes your identity, names a true wound for people who turn every result into a verdict on themselves. I share that cohort and that wound, and my own work leans on the same two-axis instinct, so I accept this as a real discipline before I press it.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:217:      "test_that_would_settle_it": "Run a small pilot in achievement-contingent or perfectionistic adults that compares three arms after comparable practice sessions: the Return Check, a resultless-practice prompt that hands the person nothing to keep, show, or measure, and a plain rest-and-plan control. Measure self-scoring frequency, rumination on Mor and Winquist style indices, and ordinary functioning at two weeks. If the Return Check raises self-monitoring or rumination relative to the resultless prompt, the model is iatrogenic for its own cohort and the counter-model wins. Add a coding test: take self-described practice-realization and Other Power instructions and try to apply the keep, release, embody return language to them. If trained coders cannot do so without importing an instrumental frame the texts reject, then return is a category the comparer adds, not one the practice has.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:230:        "The Return Check should be demoted from a general practice to a gated option for bypassing, self-display, avoidance, or peak-chasing."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:235:        "Dogen practice-realization and Shinran's no-calculation pressure are not edge cases; they require a prior scope gate.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:239:      "counter_model": "A scope-gated model is stronger. First ask whether the practice claims a result that the practitioner can possess, display, regulate, or misread. If yes, a return test may be useful. If no, especially in practice-realization or Other Power frames, the right response may be to stop importing result language. Second ask whether the practitioner is a bypasser or a compulsive scorer. The bypasser may need return-to-conduct pressure; the compulsive scorer may need a resultless prompt that hands them nothing to grade.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:243:      "fairness_check": "The idea now serves a narrower cohort: stable adults already using contemplative practice, prayer, study, therapy-adjacent reflection, or disciplined work who tend to use peak states, insight, or achievement as identity proof. It does not fit acute crisis, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, dissociation, trauma activation, scrupulosity, destabilizing meditation experiences, formal lineage contexts where a teacher or vow governs aftercare, or people whose main wound is compulsive self-monitoring rather than bypassing.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:246:      "remaining_risk": "Even narrowed, the language of return can still moralize ordinary life if readers hear it as output, usefulness, or productivity. The public teaching must avoid scorekeeping language and may need two separate practices: one for bypassing after insight, and one for exhausted self-measurers who need permission to stop making themselves into a project.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:247:      "revised_claim": "For stable adults who already practice, reflect, study, pray, meditate, or work intensely, and whose human problem is achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout risk, peak-chasing, or using insight as identity proof, a practice earns only provisional trust when it helps them return to ordinary life with less self-possession and more availability for care, repair, rest, and necessary work. This is not a universal test of all practice. Before applying it, ask two gates: does the practice itself claim or permit a result that can be kept, released, or embodied; and is this person mainly bypassing responsibility or mainly trapped in compulsive self-evaluation. The return test fits the bypasser, the self-displayer, and the person who uses experience to avoid conduct. It does not fit the compulsive self-measurer, the acutely distressed person, the dissociative or scrupulous person, the person in addiction withdrawal or severe depression, destabilizing meditation cases, or traditions whose own discipline forbids self-calculation. For those cases, the better first practice may be resultless rest, plain support, teacher-guided aftercare, clinical care, or a non-evaluative next action.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:251:        "Shinran, Tannisho, and jinen honi",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:252:        "Dogen, Bendowa, shusho-itto",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:253:        "MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:260:      "test_that_would_settle_it": "Run the three-arm pilot Claude proposed, but stratify participants first by bypassing tendency versus compulsive self-evaluation. Compare a revised non-scored Return Prompt, a resultless-practice prompt, and a plain rest-and-plan control after comparable practice sessions for two weeks. Measure rumination, self-focused attention, self-scoring frequency, affect, avoidance, and ordinary functioning. The revised model is supported only if the Return Prompt helps bypassers without increasing rumination, while the resultless prompt does better for compulsive scorers. Add a source-coding test for Dogen, Shinran, MN 22, Heart Sutra, and Rinzai materials. If coders cannot apply keep, release, or embody without importing instrumentality, the model must stay limited to practices that permit result language.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:277:        "The scope gate, does the practice claim a possessable result, genuinely answers my appropriation worry for practice-realization and Other Power frames.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:293:        "Shinran, Tannisho, and jinen honi (no calculation by the practicer)",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:294:        "Dogen, Bendowa, shusho-itto (practice and realization are one)",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:299:      "test_that_would_settle_it": "Keep the Proponent's stratified three-arm pilot, but add the decisive variable: who administers the gate. Within the compulsive-scorer stratum, compare self-administered gating against externally administered gating, where a teacher or clinician assigns keep, set down, or embody and the participant does not self-rate. If externally held gating lowers rumination while self-held gating raises it relative to the resultless prompt, the gate is safe only off the self for that stratum, and the model must say so. Add one more probe for the oscillator: track within-person switching between bypassing and compulsive-scoring across the two weeks; if a meaningful fraction switch arms, the binary gate is too coarse and needs a state-level, not trait-level, assignment.",
